UID:briclab-film-tv-residency-2026-27@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260529T085824Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260605
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260606
SUMMARY:Deadline: BRIClab: Film + TV Residency 2026/27 (Brooklyn)
DESCRIPTION:BRIClab Film + TV residency at BRIC in Brooklyn\, supporting em
 erging-to-mid-career documentary filmmakers to develop a project with a st
 ipend\, production funds\, equipment and post-production access\, and ment
 orship. ELIGIBILITY: NYC-based documentary filmmakers\, individuals or duo
 s\; the programme prioritises disabled\, BIPOC and LGBTQ+ artists. Apply v
 ia the BRIC opportunity page.\n\nOrganisation: BRIC\nLocation: Brooklyn\, 
 New York\, USA (NYC-based)\nAward: $2\,500 stipend plus up to $2\,000 in p
 roduction costs\, alongside equipment and post-production access and mento
 rship. No application fee.\nDuration: Residency across 2026/27\n\nMore: ht
 tps://bricartsmedia.org/art-artists/opportunity/briclab/film-tv/
URL:https://bricartsmedia.org/art-artists/opportunity/briclab/film-tv/
LOCATION:Brooklyn\, New York\, USA (NYC-based)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:arts-council-england-dycp-round-24-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260529T085824Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260702
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260703
SUMMARY:Deadline: Arts Council England: Developing Your Creative Practice (
 DYCP) Round 24
DESCRIPTION:Developing Your Creative Practice (DYCP) supports individual cr
 eative and cultural practitioners in England to take time to develop their
  practice\, across all disciplines including digital and media arts. The f
 unding is for practice development (research\, training\, mentoring\, trav
 el\, experimentation) rather than producing or presenting finished work. E
 LIGIBILITY: England-based independent creative practitioners with a track 
 record who work outside the major-funded organisations. Round 24 opens 4 J
 une 2026 (12:00) and closes 2 July 2026. Apply via the Arts Council Englan
 d DYCP page.\n\nOrganisation: Arts Council England\nLocation: England\, UK
 \nAward: GBP 1\,000 to GBP 12\,000 per individual for creative-practice de
 velopment (research\, training\, time to think\, travel\, mentoring\, etc.
 ). No application fee.\nDuration: Project-based (practice-development peri
 od)\n\nMore: https://www.artscouncil.org.uk/dycp
URL:https://www.artscouncil.org.uk/dycp
LOCATION:England\, UK
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:john-hansard-gallery-disabled-artists-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260529T085824Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260525
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260526
SUMMARY:Deadline: John Hansard Gallery: Open Call for Disabled Artists 2026
  (Future Curators)
DESCRIPTION:Open call from John Hansard Gallery for one disabled artist to 
 collaborate with Occupational Therapy and Engineering students at the Univ
 ersity of Southampton to make or adapt tools that support their artistic p
 ractice. The tools and resulting artwork are displayed in an exhibition at
  John Hansard Gallery in February 2027\, curated by Jess Starns as part of
  the Future Curators Programme\, a disability-justice residency programme 
 for Disabled curators founded by the Disabled artist-led organisation DASH
 . The work involves collaborating with students in July and August\, testi
 ng and refining the tools through autumn\, and creating artwork for the ex
 hibition. ELIGIBILITY: disabled artists living and working within a 40-mil
 e distance of John Hansard Gallery. Submit an Expression of Interest via t
 he gallery's open-call page\; access requirements supported (contact jenni
 fa@jhg.art).\n\nOrganisation: John Hansard Gallery\, with the University o
 f Southampton (part of the DASH Future Curators Programme)\nLocation: With
 in 40 miles of John Hansard Gallery\, Southampton\, UK\nAward: GBP 2\,000 
 artist fee (including up to four meetings with students)\, plus travel exp
 enses\, access costs and a materials budget to be defined. No application 
 fee.\nDuration: Project running July 2026 to a February 2027 exhibition\n\
 nMore: https://jhg.art/events/open-call-disabled-artists/
URL:https://jhg.art/events/open-call-disabled-artists/
LOCATION:Within 40 miles of John Hansard Gallery\, Southampton\, UK
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:vas-bothy-project-sweeneys-bothy-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260529T085824Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260614
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260615
SUMMARY:Deadline: Visual Arts Scotland x Bothy Project: Sweeney's Bothy Res
 idency 2026 (Isle of Eigg)
DESCRIPTION:Sixth year of Visual Arts Scotland's residency in partnership w
 ith Bothy Project\, offering a week at Sweeney's Bothy\, an off-grid\, pur
 pose-built artist residency space on the Isle of Eigg in the Scottish Inne
 r Hebrides. As the residency is only a week long\, there is no expectation
  to produce a body of work\; the purpose is time to reflect on practice\, 
 develop ideas and engage with the island's environment and culture. ELIGIB
 ILITY: open to any creative discipline (visual arts\, craft and design\, m
 usic\, literature\, performance\, and researchers/thinkers)\, but applican
 ts must be a VAS member at both the time of application and the time of re
 sidency. Applicants are asked to be mindful of the island community's etho
 s of environmental sustainability and to travel sustainably (cars are not 
 permitted for non-residents). The successful applicant undertakes a VAS In
 stagram takeover and documents their experience. Apply by email to admin@v
 isualartsscotland.org plus the online form\, with six images of recent wor
 k on a single PDF.\n\nOrganisation: Visual Arts Scotland (VAS)\, in partne
 rship with Bothy Project\nLocation: Sweeney's Bothy\, Isle of Eigg\, Scott
 ish Inner Hebrides\, UK (off-grid)\nAward: GBP 720 artist fee\, plus reaso
 nable travel up to GBP 250 and accommodation costs included. No applicatio
 n fee.\nDuration: One-week residency (10 to 17 October 2026)\n\nMore: http
 s://www.visualartsscotland.org/opportunity/bothy-project-residency-2026/
URL:https://www.visualartsscotland.org/opportunity/bothy-project-residency-
 2026/
LOCATION:Sweeney's Bothy\, Isle of Eigg\, Scottish Inner Hebrides\, UK (off
 -grid)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:decoratelier-workspacebrussels-residency-2026@artificialnouveau.github.
 io
DTSTAMP:20260529T085824Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260531
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260601
SUMMARY:Deadline: workspacebrussels: Decoratelier Open Call 2026 (Spatial R
 esearch Residency)
DESCRIPTION:Research-focused residency at Decoratelier in Molenbeek\, organ
 ised through workspacebrussels\, for artists and collectives working with 
 space\, scenography\, installation\, architecture and performative environ
 ments. The residency prioritises research and material experimentation ove
 r production: applicants propose an investigation into spatial practice\, 
 ephemeral architecture or scenographic experimentation connected to the pe
 rforming arts\, engaging directly with the warehouse architecture and reus
 able materials. ELIGIBILITY: artists or collectives based in Belgium or ab
 road. NOTE: this is a context-specific research residency and does not pro
 vide scenographic support for existing productions. Apply via the workspac
 ebrussels Decoratelier open call.\n\nOrganisation: workspacebrussels (resi
 dency at Decoratelier\, Molenbeek)\nLocation: Decoratelier\, Molenbeek\, B
 russels\, Belgium\nAward: EUR 5\,000 budget (incl. VAT) for the residency\
 , plus a 10x18m warehouse hall\, wood and metal workshop access\, reusable
  materials\, junior-builder support three days a week\, artistic and techn
 ical feedback\, a possible internal showing\, and weekday lunch. No applic
 ation fee.\nDuration: Three-week research residency (5 to 23 October 2026)
 \n\nMore: https://www.workspacebrussels.be/en
URL:https://www.workspacebrussels.be/en
LOCATION:Decoratelier\, Molenbeek\, Brussels\, Belgium
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:mdd-collective-open-call-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260529T085824Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260614
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260615
SUMMARY:Deadline: Museum Dhondt-Dhaenens: MDD Collective Open Call 2026
DESCRIPTION:Open call from Museum Dhondt-Dhaenens' youth collective invitin
 g three to four emerging artists to present a work in the museum garden ov
 er the weekend of 11-12 July 2026\, in dialogue with its surroundings\, ar
 chitecture and landscape. The theme centres on the idea of the 'frame'\, s
 tarting from Isa Genzken's work Fenster in the museum garden\, exploring h
 ow a frame determines what we see and what stays just outside our field of
  vision. ELIGIBILITY: emerging artists aged 31 or under interested in join
 ing MDD's youth project. Apply via the Museum Dhondt-Dhaenens open-call pa
 ge\; questions to opencall@museumdd.be.\n\nOrganisation: Museum Dhondt-Dha
 enens (MDD) youth collective\nLocation: Museum Dhondt-Dhaenens garden\, Si
 nt-Martens-Latem\, Belgium (outdoor presentation)\nAward: EUR 500 material
  budget plus a EUR 350 participation fee per selected artist\; transport a
 nd insurance of the works are fully covered by the organisation. No applic
 ation fee.\nDuration: One-weekend presentation (11-12 July 2026)\n\nMore: 
 https://museumdd.be/en/event/open-call-mdd-collective
URL:https://museumdd.be/en/event/open-call-mdd-collective
LOCATION:Museum Dhondt-Dhaenens garden\, Sint-Martens-Latem\, Belgium (outd
 oor presentation)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:jan-van-eyck-material-research-fellowships-2027@artificialnouveau.githu
 b.io
DTSTAMP:20260529T085824Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260624
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260625
SUMMARY:Deadline: Jan van Eyck Academie: Material Research Fellowships 2027
  (Future Materials)
DESCRIPTION:Two material-research fellowships at the Jan van Eyck Academie 
 under the Future Materials programme: one Fashion & Textile Material Fello
 wship and one Future Materials Fellowship\, each lasting 11 months. The pr
 ogramme supports environmentally conscious art and design practices resear
 ching sustainable\, non-toxic\, biobased alternatives to fossil-based or t
 oxic materials. ELIGIBILITY: applicants with an existing research project 
 on sustainable/biobased materials (the Fashion & Textile stream focuses on
  fashion/textile systems\; the Future Materials stream on biobased materia
 ls or processes for broad creative use). Projects should take a systemic p
 erspective on the just transition. Jan van Eyck alumni\, and full-time alu
 mni of the Rijksakademie or De Ateliers\, are not eligible. Fellows develo
 p their project with the Jan van Eyck Labs and Maastricht partners (Textil
 e Innovation Maastricht\; CHILL at Brightlands Chemelot Campus). Apply via
  the respective Jan van Eyck application form.\n\nOrganisation: Jan van Ey
 ck Academie (Future Materials / Future Threads programme\, co-funded by th
 e EU Just Transition Fund)\nLocation: Maastricht\, Netherlands (residency\
 ; fellows must reside within 10km)\nAward: Monthly stipend of EUR 1\,750 (
 80% exempt from income tax) plus an annual working budget of EUR 2\,250\, 
 a private studio apartment\, and access to the Jan van Eyck Labs and exter
 nal partners. Application fee EUR 50 excl. VAT (waived for applicants from
  DAC-list lower-income countries and territories).\nDuration: 11 months (1
 5 January to 15 December 2027)\n\nMore: https://www.janvaneyck.nl/calendar
 /2-material-research-fellowships-2027/
URL:https://www.janvaneyck.nl/calendar/2-material-research-fellowships-2027
 /
LOCATION:Maastricht\, Netherlands (residency\; fellows must reside within 1
 0km)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:tanztage-berlin-open-call-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260529T085824Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260705
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260706
SUMMARY:Deadline: Tanztage Berlin Open Call 2027 (Sophiensaele)
DESCRIPTION:Tanztage Berlin\, the long-running platform at Sophiensaele for
  emerging choreographers and performance makers\, is accepting application
 s for its 2027 edition (the final edition under artistic director Mateusz 
 Szymanowka). The festival supports work across contemporary dance\, choreo
 graphy\, installation\, video and expanded performance formats\, in two tr
 acks: premieres (new productions) and revivals (completed works). ELIGIBIL
 ITY: emerging artists connected to Berlin (early in their careers\, newly 
 living in Berlin\, or without prior Berlin project funding)\; a meaningful
  professional relationship to the city is required\, though formal residen
 cy registration is not. The festival particularly welcomes projects involv
 ing marginalised perspectives\, intergenerational casts and disabled artis
 ts. Apply via the Tanztage Berlin open-call page.\n\nOrganisation: Sophien
 saele (Tanztage Berlin)\nLocation: Sophiensaele\, Berlin\, Germany\nAward:
  Premieres receive EUR 10\,000 to EUR 18\,000 production support\; revival
 s receive a EUR 5\,000 flat fee. Both tracks also receive a EUR 410 evenin
 g fee per person per performance\, rehearsal space\, technical\, curatoria
 l\, dramaturgical and PR support\, and photo/video documentation. No appli
 cation fee.\nDuration: Festival 7-23 January 2027 (rehearsals from Novembe
 r 2026)\n\nMore: https://sophiensaele.com/en
URL:https://sophiensaele.com/en
LOCATION:Sophiensaele\, Berlin\, Germany
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:film-london-flamin-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260529T085824Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260601
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260602
SUMMARY:Deadline: Film London: The FLAMIN Fellowship 2026
DESCRIPTION:The FLAMIN Fellowship from Film London supports early-career ar
 tists working in moving image with a development bursary and a structured 
 year-long career-development programme. ELIGIBILITY: England-based moving-
 image artists with roughly 2 to 5 years of professional practice outside h
 igher education and at least two prior exhibited or screened works\; exclu
 des current students\, gallery-represented artists\, those with major solo
  institutional shows\, and film-industry professionals. Apply via the Film
  London FLAMIN Fellowship page by midnight on 1 June 2026.\n\nOrganisation
 : Film London (FLAMIN - Film London Artists' Moving Image Network)\, with 
 Arts Council England\nLocation: England\, UK (year-long programme with in-
 person workshops)\nAward: GBP 2\,500 project-development bursary per artis
 t\, plus a year-long programme of monthly in-person workshops\, 1:1 sessio
 ns with a production advisor\, screening and promotion\, and a peer commun
 ity. Stage-2 interviewees also receive a GBP 100 interview fee. No applica
 tion fee.\nDuration: One-year fellowship programme\n\nMore: https://filmlo
 ndon.org.uk/resource/apply-to-the-flamin-fellowship
URL:https://filmlondon.org.uk/resource/apply-to-the-flamin-fellowship
LOCATION:England\, UK (year-long programme with in-person workshops)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:artists-futures-fund-breakthrough-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.git
 hub.io
DTSTAMP:20260529T085824Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260612
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260613
SUMMARY:Deadline: Artists' Futures Fund: Breakthrough Artist Fellowship 202
 6-27
DESCRIPTION:Needs-based fellowship from the Artists' Futures Fund bridging 
 the gap from graduation to professional visual-arts practice. ELIGIBILITY:
  recent BA or MA visual-arts graduates (within two years of October 2026) 
 from an AFF partner institution (Cardiff School of Art & Design\, Chichest
 er College Group\, Liverpool Hope\, Loughborough\, Manchester Metropolitan
 \, City of Portsmouth College\, Sunderland\, Swansea College of Art UWTSD)
 \, or a relevant Level 3 UAL Diploma/A Levels from City of Portsmouth Coll
 ege\; must be eligible to live and work in England or Wales\, facing socio
 -economic\, mental and/or physical health barriers\, and able to commit fu
 lly to the 10 months without additional formal study. Applications open 15
  May 2026. Apply via the Artists' Futures Fund support page.\n\nOrganisati
 on: Artists' Futures Fund\nLocation: England and Wales\, UK (in-kind studi
 o space at a partner institution)\nAward: GBP 10\,000 unrestricted bursary
  over the 10-month fellowship\, plus in-kind studio space\, mentorship fro
 m a partner institution\, professional development\, and a co-curated end-
 of-fellowship group showcase. No application fee.\nDuration: 10 months (Oc
 tober 2026 to July 2027)\n\nMore: https://www.artistsfuturesfund.org/oursu
 pport
URL:https://www.artistsfuturesfund.org/oursupport
LOCATION:England and Wales\, UK (in-kind studio space at a partner institut
 ion)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:art-zoyd-studios-residency-2026-27@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260529T085824Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260529
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260530
SUMMARY:Deadline: Art Zoyd Studios: Electroacoustic & Electronic Music Resi
 dency 2026/2027
DESCRIPTION:Production residency at Art Zoyd Studios in Valenciennes for co
 mposers\, musicians and sound artists working in electroacoustic and elect
 ronic music\, with technical support from a computer-music designer to dev
 elop new work. ELIGIBILITY: composers\, musicians and artists practising i
 n electroacoustic or electronic music\; open worldwide. Apply via the Art 
 Zoyd Studios residency request page.\n\nOrganisation: Art Zoyd Studios\nLo
 cation: Valenciennes\, France (in-person residency)\nAward: Funded residen
 cy: accommodation and meals covered during the residency\, travel reimburs
 ed up to EUR 400\, and support from a computer-music designer\; a copyrigh
 t bonus is possible. No artist fee or stipend. No application fee.\nDurati
 on: Residency across the 2026/2027 season\n\nMore: https://artzoydstudios.
 com/en/demande-residence/
URL:https://artzoydstudios.com/en/demande-residence/
LOCATION:Valenciennes\, France (in-person residency)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:realities-in-transition-rit2-telepresence-2026@artificialnouveau.github
 .io
DTSTAMP:20260529T085824Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260610
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260611
SUMMARY:Deadline: Realities in Transition: RiT 2 Open Call #2 - Telepresenc
 e in the Digital Space
DESCRIPTION:Open call from the Realities in Transition (RiT 2 - Unwritten W
 orlds) programme for artists and designers to co-create a collective XR ar
 twork during a residency exploring telepresence and the shifting nature of
  presence in the digital age. The residency investigates how the body oper
 ates across physical and digital dimensions through motion capture and imm
 ersive environments\, treating movement as a language that can be encoded\
 , transformed and transmitted\, and opening critical and speculative persp
 ectives on authorship\, identity and corporeality. MEDIUM: motion capture 
 and immersivity. ELIGIBILITY: individual XR and immersive artists who are 
 European residents\; three artists are selected and joined by a creative t
 echnologist to work as a group. The residency alternates shared work\, cri
 tical discussion and experimentation\, from conception and prototyping to 
 a public Test Lab and audience presentation\, with a mentoring programme c
 overing XR mediation\, ethics and inclusion\, accessibility\, hybridisatio
 n of spaces\, distribution and business models. Apply via the Realities in
  Transition open-call page.\n\nOrganisation: Realities in Transition\, in 
 collaboration with MEET Digital Culture Center Milan\nLocation: Hybrid: on
 line phases plus a two-month in-person period at MEET Digital Culture Cent
 er\, Milan\, Italy\nAward: Three grants of EUR 15\,000 each (one per artis
 t)\, covering the artist's fee plus travel\, accommodation and subsistence
 \, disbursed in three installments (EUR 7\,000 on signing\, EUR 4\,000 aft
 er the Test Lab\, EUR 4\,000 at the end). Production costs of up to EUR 5\
 ,000 are covered by the host\, plus a mentoring programme. No application 
 fee.\nDuration: Six-month hybrid residency (online October-December 2026\;
  in-person at MEET Milan January-February 2027\; online February-March 202
 7)\, final project presented June 2027\n\nMore: https://www.realities-in-t
 ransition.eu/rit-2-open-call-2/
URL:https://www.realities-in-transition.eu/rit-2-open-call-2/
LOCATION:Hybrid: online phases plus a two-month in-person period at MEET Di
 gital Culture Center\, Milan\, Italy
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:pen-america-literary-grants-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260529T085824Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260615
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260616
SUMMARY:Deadline: PEN America Literary Grants 2027
DESCRIPTION:PEN America's suite of literary grants and fellowships supporti
 ng individual writers and works in progress across genres (fiction\, nonfi
 ction\, poetry\, oral history and more)\, each with its own focus and crit
 eria. ELIGIBILITY: varies by grant\; generally US-based writers\, with sev
 eral open to writers and translators at different career stages. Distinct 
 from the PEN/Heim Translation Fund and PEN Presents. Review individual gra
 nt criteria and apply via the PEN America literary grants page.\n\nOrganis
 ation: PEN America\nLocation: United States (US-based writers)\nAward: Var
 ies by grant (e.g. PEN/Jean Stein Grant for Literary Oral History\, PEN/Ph
 yllis Naylor Working Writer Fellowship)\, generally in the $5\,000 to $10\
 ,000+ range. No application fee.\nDuration: Project / works-in-progress su
 pport\n\nMore: https://pen.org/literary-grants/
URL:https://pen.org/literary-grants/
LOCATION:United States (US-based writers)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:arte-laguna-prize-21-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260529T085824Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260630
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260701
SUMMARY:Deadline: Arte Laguna Prize 2026 (21st Edition)
DESCRIPTION:International Arte Laguna Prize\, open to artists across many m
 edia including dedicated digital art and video sections\, with a finalist 
 exhibition at the Venice Arsenale Nord. ELIGIBILITY: individual artists of
  all ages and nationalities worldwide. NOTE: an entry fee applies (roughly
  EUR 97 to EUR 122)\, but the prize awards substantial cash. Apply via the
  Arte Laguna Prize page.\n\nOrganisation: Arte Laguna (Venice)\nLocation: 
 Venice\, Italy (finalist exhibition at Arsenale Nord)\nAward: EUR 10\,000 
 main prize plus additional FOMAS prizes (EUR 7\,000 / 4\,000 / 3\,000) and
  a finalist exhibition at the Venice Arsenale Nord. Entry fee approximatel
 y EUR 97 to EUR 122.\nDuration: One-off prize\n\nMore: https://artelagunap
 rize.com/21-edition/
URL:https://artelagunaprize.com/21-edition/
LOCATION:Venice\, Italy (finalist exhibition at Arsenale Nord)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
